window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["electrophysiology"]={"slug": "electrophysiology", "title": "Electrophysiology & Devices", "tagline": "From the sinus node to the shock coil: conduction physiology, bradyarrhythmia pacing, ICD and CRT selection, and the device skills a fellow is expected to own — reading the chest film, the NBG code, and the interrogation report.", "level": 3, "readMin": 44, "takeaways": ["A pacemaker treats bradycardia, an ICD treats ventricular tachyarrhythmia by pacing or shocking, and a CRT device resynchronizes the failing wide-QRS ventricle; the CXR tells you which one is in the chest by counting leads and finding the shock coil.", "The RV lead of an ICD carries one or two thick radiopaque shock coils — that single finding on the chest film distinguishes an ICD/CRT-D from a plain pacemaker faster than any other clue.", "The NBG code reads chamber-paced, chamber-sensed, response-to-sensing, rate-response: DDD is the physiologic dual-chamber default, VVI is backup ventricular pacing, and the R means rate-adaptive.", "A magnet over a pacemaker forces asynchronous pacing at a battery-indicating rate; a magnet over an ICD suspends tachytherapy but does NOT change pacing — confusing these two behaviors is a classic and dangerous error.", "On interrogation, walk the same four rails every time: battery/ERI, lead integrity (impedance, sensing, capture threshold), burden (percent paced, percent biventricular pacing), and arrhythmia log with delivered therapies.", "CRT helps most in sinus rhythm with LBBB, QRS at least 150 ms, and LVEF at most 35% on guideline-directed therapy; the wider and more LBBB-shaped the QRS, the better the response."], "sections": [{"id": "learning-objectives", "title": "Learning objectives", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "This module carries an internal medicine resident to first-year electrophysiology-aware fellow depth, with a deliberate and heavy emphasis on cardiac implantable electronic devices. It assumes you can read a basic ECG and recognize the common tachyarrhythmias, and it builds the device-reasoning layer that separates a consulting fellow from a covering resident."}, {"type": "list", "items": ["Trace the normal conduction cascade and connect each structure to the rhythm disturbance produced when it fails.", "State the guideline indications for permanent pacing, and choose single-chamber versus dual-chamber systems.", "Distinguish a pacemaker from an ICD from a CRT device on a chest radiograph by counting leads, locating each tip, and finding the shock coil.", "Read the NBG pacing-mode code and predict device behavior, including the response to a magnet.", "Interpret a device interrogation report the way a fellow rounds on it: battery, leads, burden, and arrhythmia log."]}, {"type": "list", "depth": 2, "items": ["Apply the primary- and secondary-prevention ICD trials (MADIT-II, SCD-HeFT, DINAMIT, DANISH) to real candidates.", "Select CRT candidates by rhythm, QRS morphology, and width, and predict response.", "Run the perioperative and MRI device workflow, including exactly what a magnet does over each device type.", "Build an antiarrhythmic and AV-nodal drug framework by Vaughan Williams class with real starting doses and monitoring."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "The device consult is graded on three reflexes: identify the hardware from the film, predict its behavior from the programmed mode, and read the interrogation without the rep. Everything below is built around those three skills."}]}, {"id": "why-it-matters", "title": "Why it matters", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Devices are the one cardiology subspecialty that follows the patient into every other service. The pre-op clinic, the MRI suite, the OR, the ICU, and the code all generate a device question, and the answer usually falls to the cardiology fellow at 2 a.m. A resident who cannot tell a pacemaker from an ICD on the chest film, or who thinks a magnet turns a pacemaker off, is a liability in exactly those moments."}, {"type": "p", "text": "The stakes are asymmetric. Misjudging a defibrillator as a pacemaker can mean a patient goes into the electrocautery field with active tachytherapy and gets shocked by their own device, or conversely that therapy stays suspended after surgery and the patient dies of an untreated ventricular arrhythmia. The skills in this module are not academic; they are the difference between a safe perioperative course and a preventable death."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The single most useful device reflex on any chest film: find the right ventricular lead and ask whether it has a thick radiopaque segment. If yes, it is a defibrillator; if no, it is a pacemaker. That one observation reorganizes the entire clinical plan."}]}, {"id": "conduction-physiology", "title": "Conduction physiology: where rhythms are born and where they break", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The impulse begins in the sinoatrial node in the high right atrium, spreads across both atria producing the P wave, and funnels into the atrioventricular node, the only normal electrical bridge between atria and ventricles. The AV node deliberately delays conduction (the PR interval) to allow atrial systole to complete before the ventricles fire. It then hands off to the His bundle, which divides into the right bundle and the left bundle; the left bundle splits into anterior and posterior fascicles, and the Purkinje network delivers the impulse to ventricular myocardium, producing the narrow QRS of synchronous activation."}, {"type": "p", "text": "Read the conduction system as a hierarchy of pacemakers with descending intrinsic rates. The sinus node fires near 60 to 100, the AV junction near 40 to 60, and ventricular escape near 20 to 40. Wherever conduction fails, the rate you see reflects the level of the next escape focus, and that level tells you where the block sits and how dangerous it is."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Sinus node dysfunction (sick sinus syndrome)", "def": "Inappropriate sinus bradycardia, sinus pauses/arrest, chronotropic incompetence, or the tachy-brady syndrome. A common pacing indication when symptomatic; it does not by itself threaten sudden death because escape rhythms remain."}, {"term": "First-degree AV block", "def": "PR over 200 ms, every P conducts. Benign in isolation; marked prolongation (over 300 ms) can be symptomatic (pseudo-pacemaker syndrome)."}, {"term": "Mobitz I (Wenckebach)", "def": "Progressive PR lengthening until a dropped beat; block is in the AV node, usually vagally mediated and benign. Responds to atropine."}, {"term": "Mobitz II", "def": "Fixed PR with sudden non-conducted P waves; block is infra-nodal (His-Purkinje). Unstable, progresses to complete block, and is a pacing indication regardless of symptoms."}, {"term": "Complete (third-degree) AV block", "def": "AV dissociation with an escape rhythm. A wide, slow escape implies an infra-nodal, unreliable pacemaker and demands pacing; atropine may paradoxically worsen infranodal block."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "The clinically load-bearing split is nodal versus infranodal. Nodal disease (Mobitz I) responds to atropine and often needs no device; infranodal disease (Mobitz II, most complete heart block with a wide escape) does not respond to atropine and needs pacing. Atropine can even accelerate the sinus rate, deliver more P waves to a diseased His-Purkinje system, and worsen the block ratio."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic</strong> — Mobitz <em>I</em> = block <em>I</em>n the node (safe, atropine works); Mobitz <em>II</em> = block below, needs a device. The Roman numeral counts how deep the lesion sits."}]}, {"id": "pacing-indications", "title": "Permanent pacing: who needs a pacemaker", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Permanent pacing is indicated when bradycardia is symptomatic and irreversible, or when the conduction disease itself predicts progression to dangerous block even before symptoms appear. The 2018 ACC/AHA/HRS bradycardia guideline organizes indications by anatomic level, and the recurring theme is that reversible causes (drugs, ischemia, hyperkalemia, hypothyroidism, Lyme carditis, vagal surges, sleep apnea) must be excluded first."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/crt-xray.png", "alt": "CRT device on radiograph", "caption": "A biventricular (CRT) device: right-atrial, right-ventricular, and coronary-sinus/LV leads.", "credit": "Gregory Marcus, MD — CC BY 3.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Cardiac_resynchronisation_therapy.png"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Rhythm / scenario", "Pace?", "Rationale"], "rows": [["Symptomatic sinus node dysfunction", "Yes (Class I)", "Symptom-rhythm correlation is the trigger; asymptomatic bradycardia does not qualify"], ["Chronotropic incompetence with symptoms", "Yes", "Add rate response (the R in DDDR)"], ["Mobitz II second-degree AV block", "Yes, even if asymptomatic", "Infranodal, unpredictable progression to complete block"], ["Third-degree / high-grade AV block", "Yes", "Especially with wide, slow, or unreliable escape"], ["Symptomatic Mobitz I", "Yes if symptomatic", "Asymptomatic Wenckebach usually needs nothing"], ["Alternating bundle branch block", "Yes", "Advanced His-Purkinje disease"], ["AF with symptomatic bradycardia or pauses", "Yes", "Pauses over 5 s in AF are a common trigger"], ["Reversible cause (drug, Lyme, ischemia)", "No — treat the cause", "Temporary pacing may bridge; permanent device is not indicated until irreversibility is established"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Do not implant a permanent pacemaker for bradycardia that is entirely explained by a nodal-blocking drug you can stop, by Lyme carditis (which resolves with antibiotics), or by acute ischemia. Implanting into a reversible cause commits the patient to lifelong hardware and its infection risk for nothing."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Single-chamber (VVI)", "def": "One RV lead. Used for permanent AF with bradycardia where there is no organized atrium to track."}, {"term": "Dual-chamber (DDD)", "def": "RA and RV leads. Restores AV synchrony; the default for sinus node dysfunction and AV block in sinus rhythm."}, {"term": "Leadless pacemaker", "def": "Self-contained capsule fixed in the RV (e.g., Micra). Single-chamber VVI physiology, no pocket or transvenous lead; ideal when vascular access or infection risk is prohibitive. Newer platforms offer atrioventricular-synchronous (VDD) leadless pacing."}, {"term": "Conduction system pacing", "def": "His-bundle or left bundle branch area pacing to preserve a narrow, physiologic QRS instead of pacing the RV apex; increasingly used to avoid pacing-induced cardiomyopathy and as an alternative to CRT."}]}]}, {"id": "device-taxonomy", "title": "Pacemaker vs ICD vs CRT: what each device actually does", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Three device families cover almost every implant, and confusing them is the commonest resident error. A pacemaker treats slow rhythms only. An implantable cardioverter-defibrillator treats fast ventricular rhythms and also contains full pacemaker function as backup. A cardiac resynchronization device adds a third lead to re-coordinate a dyssynchronous failing ventricle, and it comes in a pacemaker-only flavor (CRT-P) or a defibrillator flavor (CRT-D)."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/icd-xray.jpg", "alt": "ICD on chest radiograph", "caption": "An ICD on chest radiograph — note the thick radiopaque shock coil on the RV lead (here also showing Twiddler's syndrome).", "credit": "Lesnick, Cooper & Doshi (CPCEM 2019) — CC BY 4.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Twiddler's_syndrome.jpg"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Device", "Primary job", "Leads (typical)", "Can it shock?", "Core indication"], "rows": [["Pacemaker (PPM)", "Treat bradycardia", "1 (RV) or 2 (RA+RV)", "No", "Symptomatic brady, AV block, SND"], ["ICD", "Terminate VT/VF", "1 (RV, with coil) ± RA", "Yes", "LVEF ≤35% primary prevention; VT/VF secondary prevention"], ["CRT-P", "Resynchronize + pace", "3 (RA, RV, LV via CS)", "No", "HFrEF, LBBB, wide QRS, no ICD need"], ["CRT-D", "Resynchronize + defibrillate", "3 (RA, RV-coil, LV)", "Yes", "HFrEF meeting both CRT and ICD criteria"]]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "An ICD is best understood as a pacemaker with a high-voltage circuit and a shock coil bolted on. It provides three tiers of therapy: bradycardia pacing exactly like a pacemaker, antitachycardia pacing (ATP — bursts of rapid pacing that can painlessly terminate monomorphic VT by capturing the reentrant circuit), and high-voltage shocks (up to roughly 35 to 40 J) for VT that ATP fails to break or for VF. Modern programming exhausts ATP before shocking because painless termination is always preferable, and uses long detection windows and high rate cut-offs (as validated by MADIT-RIT) to avoid shocking self-terminating or slow arrhythmias."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Subcutaneous ICD (S-ICD)", "def": "A defibrillator with no transvenous lead — the coil runs in a subcutaneous parasternal tunnel and the can sits at the left mid-axillary line. It shocks VT/VF but cannot provide long-term bradycardia pacing, ATP, or CRT. Chosen to avoid vascular/lead complications in young patients or those without a pacing need."}, {"term": "Antitachycardia pacing (ATP)", "def": "A train of ventricular pacing faster than the tachycardia to penetrate and terminate a reentrant VT circuit painlessly. First-line for monomorphic VT below the VF zone."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "When you are told a patient has a defibrillator, immediately ask which subtype, because it changes the perioperative plan. A transvenous ICD responds to a magnet by suspending shocks; an S-ICD magnet also suspends shocks but has different beep confirmation and no pacing to worry about; a CRT-D magnet suspends shocks while leaving biventricular pacing running — and losing that pacing intraoperatively would be a separate problem if you reprogrammed instead of using a magnet."}]}, {"id": "cxr-identification", "title": "Reading the device on the chest radiograph", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The chest film is the fastest bedside device identification tool and it is fair game on rounds and boards. Work it systematically every time: locate the generator, count the leads, trace each lead to its tip, and hunt for shock coils. Those four steps name the device without an interrogation."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["A four-step read of any device film"], "items": ["<strong>Generator:</strong> a radiopaque can in the left (occasionally right) pre-pectoral pocket. A bulkier can with a visible capacitor usually means an ICD rather than a slim pacemaker.", "<strong>Count the leads</strong> leaving the header: one = single-chamber, two = dual-chamber, three = biventricular (CRT).", "<strong>Trace each tip:</strong> right atrial appendage lead makes a gentle J-hook in the high right atrium; RV lead crosses the tricuspid to the RV apex pointing toward the left chest and slightly inferior/anterior; the LV lead courses up and laterally over the cardiac silhouette because it sits in a coronary sinus tributary on the epicardial LV free wall.", "<strong>Find the coil(s):</strong> scan the RV lead for one or two thick, dense, radiopaque segments — the shock coils. Their presence means ICD or CRT-D. No coil means pacemaker or CRT-P."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Leads seen", "Coil on RV lead?", "Third lateral (LV) lead?", "Device"], "rows": [["1", "No", "No", "Single-chamber pacemaker (VVI)"], ["2", "No", "No", "Dual-chamber pacemaker (DDD)"], ["1", "Yes", "No", "Single-chamber ICD"], ["2", "Yes", "No", "Dual-chamber ICD"], ["3", "No", "Yes", "CRT-P (biventricular pacemaker)"], ["3", "Yes", "Yes", "CRT-D"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "The shock coil is the whole game on the film. A defibrillator lead has a segment that is visibly thicker and more radiopaque than the rest of the wire — often two such segments (a distal RV coil and a proximal SVC coil). A pacing lead is a uniform thin wire to its tip. Learn to spot the coil at a glance and device identification becomes a two-second read."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The LV lead is the one residents miss because it does not point where a lead 'should.' It enters the coronary sinus from the right atrium, then travels posterolaterally over the LV epicardium, so on the frontal film it drapes up-and-out toward the left shoulder rather than diving to the apex. If you see a third lead heading laterally over the heart border, you are looking at CRT. Also scan for retained/abandoned leads and for lead fractures or a header-connector 'twiddler' appearance."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Annotated device chest radiographs showing lead courses, single/dual/biventricular systems, and the ICD shock coil as a thick radiopaque segment.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia — cardiac device chest radiograph examples"}]}, {"id": "nbg-code", "title": "Pacing modes and the NBG code", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Programmed behavior is described by the five-letter NASPE/BPEG (NBG) generic code. In practice you use the first four positions. Read them in order and the device's logic falls out: what it paces, what it senses, what it does when it senses, and whether it speeds up with activity."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Position", "Meaning", "Common letters"], "rows": [["I", "Chamber(s) PACED", "O, A, V, D (A+V)"], ["II", "Chamber(s) SENSED", "O, A, V, D"], ["III", "RESPONSE to sensing", "O (none), I (inhibit), T (trigger), D (inhibit+track)"], ["IV", "Rate modulation", "R (rate-adaptive sensor on), or blank"], ["V", "Multisite pacing", "rarely used; O/A/V/D"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "DDD", "def": "Paces and senses both chambers; a sensed atrial beat triggers ventricular pacing (tracking) and a sensed ventricular beat inhibits. The physiologic default that preserves AV synchrony."}, {"term": "VVI", "def": "Paces and senses the ventricle only; a sensed R wave inhibits the next pace. Backup ventricular pacing — used in permanent AF where there is no atrium worth tracking."}, {"term": "AAI", "def": "Paces and senses the atrium only. Appropriate only when AV conduction is intact (isolated sinus node dysfunction); rarely used alone because AV block can develop later."}, {"term": "DDDR / VVIR", "def": "The same modes with rate response on — an accelerometer or minute-ventilation sensor raises the paced rate during activity for chronotropically incompetent patients."}, {"term": "DOO / VOO", "def": "Asynchronous pacing: paces at a fixed rate, senses nothing, inhibits for nothing. This is the mode a magnet forces on a pacemaker and the mode you want during electrocautery."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic</strong> — read NBG as <em>Paced, Sensed, Response, Rate</em>: 'Position 1 what I <em>Pace</em>, position 2 what I <em>Sense</em>, position 3 my <em>Reaction</em>, position 4 do I <em>Run faster</em>.' D in the third slot uniquely means both inhibit and track, which is why DDD both suppresses competing beats and follows the atrium."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "Rate response has a downside you will be consulted about: a hyperactive accelerometer can pace a patient into inappropriate tachycardia during shivering, dental drilling, or on a bumpy transport, and minute-ventilation sensors can be tricked by mechanical ventilation. If a paced patient is inexplicably tachycardic, sensor-driven rate response is on the differential."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Paced-rhythm ECG examples showing atrial, ventricular, and biventricular pacing spikes, plus loss of capture and undersensing.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — pacemaker rhythms"}]}, {"id": "magnet-behavior", "title": "Magnet behavior: the two rules you cannot mix up", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "A clinical magnet does completely different things over a pacemaker versus an ICD, and confusing the two is one of the most dangerous device errors a trainee makes. Memorize both rules as a pair, because the whole point is that they are not the same."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "entries": [{"term": "Magnet over a PACEMAKER", "def": "Forces asynchronous pacing (VOO/DOO) at a fixed magnet rate, ignoring the patient's own rhythm and any electrical interference. The magnet rate encodes battery status — a drop in magnet rate signals approaching end of life. Pacing does NOT stop; it becomes competitive."}, {"term": "Magnet over an ICD", "def": "Suspends tachyarrhythmia detection and therapy — no shocks, no ATP — for as long as the magnet sits over it. It does NOT change pacing at all: the ICD keeps pacing in whatever mode it was programmed. Removing the magnet restores tachytherapy."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "An ICD magnet does not make the device pace asynchronously. If a pacemaker-dependent patient with an ICD goes to the OR, taping a magnet over the can suspends shocks but leaves the pacing susceptible to electrocautery oversensing and inhibition. Pacemaker-dependent ICD patients generally need formal reprogramming to an asynchronous mode, not just a magnet."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic</strong> — <em>'Magnet makes a Pacemaker Play (paces asynchronously); magnet makes an ICD Pause (its shocks).'</em> Pacemaker → paces; ICD → pauses therapy. The magnet touches pacing on one device and touches shocks on the other, never both."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Manufacturer nuances exist and you should verify rather than assume. Boston Scientific (and legacy Guidant) ICDs can be programmed so a magnet produces an audible tone — beeping in sync with each R wave means tachytherapy is still on, while a continuous steady tone means the magnet has disabled therapy — and some can be set so a magnet permanently disables therapy or is ignored entirely. Medtronic and Abbott (St. Jude) devices behave differently and are typically silent. If magnet response is critical to a case, interrogate and confirm rather than trust the default."}]}, {"id": "icd-indications", "title": "ICD indications and the trials behind them", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "ICDs are split into secondary prevention (the patient already survived a life-threatening ventricular arrhythmia) and primary prevention (the patient has never arrested but carries a high risk based mostly on ejection fraction). Secondary prevention is the stronger indication; primary prevention rests on a small number of landmark trials that every fellow should be able to name."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Indication", "Threshold / population", "Key evidence"], "rows": [["Secondary prevention", "Survived VF or hemodynamically unstable VT without reversible cause", "AVID, CIDS, CASH"], ["Primary — ischemic", "LVEF ≤35%, NYHA II–III, ≥40 days post-MI, on GDMT", "MADIT-II, SCD-HeFT"], ["Primary — ischemic, severe", "LVEF ≤30%, NYHA I", "MADIT-II"], ["Primary — non-ischemic", "LVEF ≤35%, NYHA II–III on GDMT", "SCD-HeFT (benefit); DANISH (attenuated benefit)"], ["Inherited / structural", "HCM, long QT, Brugada, ARVC, sarcoid by risk score", "Guideline risk calculators"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "The 40-day and 90-day rules", "def": "No primary-prevention ICD within 40 days of an MI or within 90 days of revascularization — DINAMIT and IRIS showed no mortality benefit implanting early after MI because non-arrhythmic death competes. Reassess EF after recovery."}, {"term": "Wait-and-reassess EF", "def": "Newly diagnosed non-ischemic cardiomyopathy needs roughly 3 months of guideline-directed medical therapy before EF is re-measured; many recover above 35% and no longer qualify."}, {"term": "DANISH (2016)", "def": "In non-ischemic cardiomyopathy, ICD reduced sudden cardiac death but did not significantly reduce all-cause mortality, partly because modern HF therapy and high CRT use lowered the competing arrhythmic risk. It made non-ischemic primary prevention a more individualized decision, especially in older patients; younger patients still appeared to benefit."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "Two disqualifiers you must actively rule out before recommending a primary-prevention ICD: a life expectancy under one year from non-cardiac disease, and an EF that has not been reassessed after adequate GDMT. A device implanted into a reversible cardiomyopathy or a dying patient adds risk without benefit."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "Primary landmark ICD trials — MADIT-II, SCD-HeFT, DINAMIT, and DANISH — for population, endpoints, and effect sizes.", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/", "label": "PubMed — ICD primary-prevention trials"}]}, {"id": "crt", "title": "Cardiac resynchronization: indications and response", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "In a failing heart with left bundle branch block, the septum and lateral wall contract out of phase; the ventricle wastes stroke work moving blood back and forth across itself. CRT places an LV lead through the coronary sinus onto the lateral epicardium and paces both ventricles nearly simultaneously, re-coordinating contraction. When it works, it is one of the few HF therapies that improves symptoms, reverse-remodels the ventricle, and reduces mortality (CARE-HF, MADIT-CRT, RAFT)."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Feature", "Strongest CRT benefit", "Weak / no benefit"], "rows": [["QRS morphology", "LBBB", "Non-LBBB (RBBB, IVCD)"], ["QRS width", "≥150 ms", "120–149 ms (modest); <120 ms none/harm"], ["Rhythm", "Sinus rhythm", "AF unless near-100% BiV pacing achieved"], ["LVEF", "≤35% on GDMT", ">35%"], ["NYHA class", "II–IV (ambulatory)", "Class I generally not indicated"], ["Sex", "Women respond at somewhat narrower QRS", "—"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic</strong> — the ideal CRT candidate is <em>'wide, blocked, and weak in sinus':</em> wide QRS ≥150 ms, LBBB block morphology, weak LVEF ≤35%, in sinus rhythm on maximal medical therapy. Move away from any one of those and the response probability falls."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "Response predictors", "def": "LBBB with QRS ≥150 ms, female sex, non-ischemic etiology, sinus rhythm, and a large baseline dyssynchrony all predict a better response. Ischemic scar in the lateral LV lead territory predicts non-response because you are pacing dead tissue."}, {"term": "Percent biventricular pacing", "def": "CRT only works when the device is actually pacing both ventricles nearly all the time. Aim for BiV pacing above 98–99%; frequent native conduction, PVCs, or uncontrolled AF that lets intrinsic beats through steals the therapy."}, {"term": "AV-junction ablation in AF", "def": "When rate-controlled AF still lets intrinsic beats fuse with paced beats and BiV percentage stays low, ablating the AV node forces 100% capture and restores CRT benefit."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "When a CRT patient is not improving, do not assume non-response — interrogate for the mechanical problem first. Suboptimal BiV pacing percentage (from AF, PVCs, long programmed AV delay, or a dislodged LV lead), a lead over scar, or an unoptimized AV/VV timing are all correctable. 'Non-responder' should be a diagnosis of exclusion after the pacing percentage is verified above 98%."}]}, {"id": "interrogation", "title": "Reading a device interrogation report", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Interrogation is where a fellow separates from a resident, because you should be able to read the printout without the industry representative narrating it. Read the same four rails every single time, in order, so nothing is missed: battery, leads, burden, and arrhythmia log. Everything on the report maps to one of those four."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["The four-rail interrogation read"], "items": ["<strong>Battery / longevity:</strong> find the voltage, projected remaining time, and the status flag. BOL (beginning of life) is normal; ERI/RRT (elective replacement indicator / recommended replacement time) means schedule a generator change within weeks to months; EOL/EOS means replace now — the device may drop to a fixed backup mode.", "<strong>Lead integrity:</strong> read each lead's pacing impedance (normal roughly 300–1200 ohms), and for ICD leads the high-voltage/shock-coil impedance (roughly 20–200 ohms). A sudden rise suggests a conductor fracture or loose set-screw; a sudden fall suggests insulation breach.", "<strong>Sensing and capture:</strong> the sensed amplitude (P wave and R wave, e.g., R over ~5 mV is comfortable) tells you the device can see native beats; the capture threshold (volts at a given pulse width) tells you the output needed to pace, and a rising threshold warns of lead maturation or micro-dislodgement.", "<strong>Burden:</strong> percent atrial paced, percent ventricular paced, and for CRT the percent biventricular pacing — the single most important CRT number.", "<strong>Arrhythmia log:</strong> AT/AF episodes and total AF burden (relevant to stroke risk and anticoagulation), plus VT/VF episodes with what therapy was delivered (ATP sequences, shocks) and whether it terminated the arrhythmia."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Parameter", "Reassuring value", "Red flag"], "rows": [["Pacing lead impedance", "~300–1200 Ω, stable", "Abrupt rise (fracture) or fall (insulation breach)"], ["Shock (HV) coil impedance", "~20–200 Ω", "Out of range → shock delivery may fail"], ["R-wave sensing", "Comfortably above threshold (e.g., >5 mV)", "Falling amplitude → undersensing risk"], ["Capture threshold", "Low and stable (e.g., <1.5 V @ 0.4 ms)", "Rising → lead problem, may lose capture"], ["Battery status", "BOL / adequate longevity", "ERI/RRT → plan generator change; EOL → replace now"], ["% BiV pacing (CRT)", ">98–99%", "<95% → therapy being stolen, investigate"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "A run of very-high-rate, nonphysiologic, saturated signals on the stored ventricular electrogram — often with make-or-break noise coincident with arm movement and a rising or erratic lead impedance — is lead fracture, not VT. This is the classic cause of inappropriate ICD shocks in a young active patient. Treat the finding as a lead problem: reprogram sensing or disable therapy while you arrange lead revision, and do not chase a phantom arrhythmia."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "A device-detected AF episode — sometimes called subclinical AF or AHRE (atrial high-rate episode) — is a real finding with management consequences. Longer-duration episodes (hours, not seconds) in a patient with vascular risk factors raise the question of anticoagulation; ARTESIA and NOAH-AFNET 6 refined this, showing a modest stroke reduction offset by bleeding, so the decision is individualized rather than automatic. Do not ignore the arrhythmia log."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "text": "<strong>Mnemonic</strong> — read every interrogation as <em>'B-L-B-A': Battery, Leads, Burden, Arrhythmias.</em> Four rails, same order, every time, and you will never leave the printout having missed the ERI flag or the untreated VT episode."}]}, {"id": "periop-mri", "title": "Perioperative and MRI device management", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "The perioperative device consult has one governing enemy: electromagnetic interference. Monopolar electrocautery near the device can be oversensed as intrinsic activity, inhibiting a pacemaker (dangerous in a pacemaker-dependent patient) or being misread by an ICD as a ventricular arrhythmia and triggering an inappropriate shock. The plan flows from two questions: is the patient pacemaker-dependent, and is the device a defibrillator?"}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "head": ["Perioperative device workflow"], "items": ["Identify the device and manufacturer; obtain a recent interrogation and determine pacemaker dependence.", "Estimate EMI exposure: monopolar cautery above the umbilicus is high risk; bipolar cautery or surgery below the umbilicus is usually low risk.", "<strong>For an ICD:</strong> suspend tachytherapy for the case — a magnet over the can (if the field allows continuous placement and the patient is not pacemaker-dependent) or formal reprogramming to therapy-off.", "<strong>For a pacemaker-dependent patient:</strong> reprogram to asynchronous pacing (VOO/DOO), or use a magnet on a pacemaker to force asynchronous pacing, so cautery cannot inhibit output.", "Have external pacing/defibrillation pads on and monitor throughout; after the case, re-enable therapies and re-interrogate before the patient leaves a monitored setting."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "The two failure modes are mirror images. In a pacemaker-dependent patient, cautery oversensing inhibits pacing and causes asystole — fix by pacing asynchronously. In an ICD patient, cautery is misread as VF and triggers an inappropriate shock — fix by suspending tachytherapy. A magnet handles each of these on the respective device, but a pacemaker-dependent ICD patient needs BOTH problems solved, which usually means reprogramming rather than a magnet alone."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "MRI is the other high-stakes environment. Legacy devices were an absolute contraindication because the static and gradient fields can heat lead tips, induce currents, and reset the device. MRI-conditional systems (both generator and all leads must be labeled conditional, with no abandoned or non-conditional leads) can be scanned under a defined protocol. Scanning of non-conditional systems is increasingly done at experienced centers under strict protocols (as in the MagnaSafe registry), but this is not equivalent to a labeled conditional system."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "MRI-conditional device", "def": "A generator-plus-lead system explicitly labeled safe under stated conditions (field strength, gradient limits, specific absorption rate). Every component, including all leads, must be conditional; a single abandoned non-conditional lead usually disqualifies the scan."}, {"term": "MRI mode", "def": "Before the scan the device is reprogrammed: for a pacemaker-dependent patient to asynchronous (DOO/VOO) so induced signals cannot inhibit it, and for a non-dependent patient often to a non-pacing (inhibited) mode; ICD tachytherapy is turned off during the scan and back on after."}, {"term": "Post-scan re-interrogation", "def": "After MRI, restore the original programming and re-interrogate to confirm parameters, thresholds, and that no reset occurred."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Even a fully MRI-conditional system requires a device team at the scanner: reprogram before, monitor with the ICD therapies off and pacing set appropriately, then reprogram and re-interrogate after. 'MRI-conditional' means safe under a protocol, not safe unattended. And remember an S-ICD or leadless device has its own separate conditional labeling — check the actual hardware, not the category."}]}, {"id": "tachyarrhythmia-drugs", "title": "Antiarrhythmic pharmacology by Vaughan Williams class", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "Whenever rhythm control or acute termination enters a device or EP discussion, you need a working antiarrhythmic framework. The Vaughan Williams classification organizes drugs by dominant channel or receptor target, and although it oversimplifies, it maps cleanly onto both the ECG effect and the toxicity you monitor."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Class", "Target / mechanism", "Representative drugs", "Signature toxicity to monitor"], "rows": [["IA", "Na+ block, intermediate; prolongs repolarization", "Procainamide, quinidine, disopyramide", "QT prolongation/torsades; procainamide → lupus-like syndrome; disopyramide anticholinergic"], ["IB", "Na+ block, fast off; shortens repolarization", "Lidocaine, mexiletine", "CNS toxicity — tremor, confusion, seizures"], ["IC", "Na+ block, slow off; marked QRS widening", "Flecainide, propafenone", "Proarrhythmia in structural heart disease (CAST); avoid with CAD/LV dysfunction"], ["II", "Beta-blockade", "Metoprolol, esmolol, carvedilol", "Bradycardia, hypotension, bronchospasm, fatigue"], ["III", "K+ block; prolongs repolarization", "Amiodarone, sotalol, dofetilide, dronedarone", "QT/torsades (uncommon with amiodarone); amiodarone organ toxicity"], ["IV", "Non-dihydropyridine Ca2+ block", "Diltiazem, verapamil", "Bradycardia, hypotension, negative inotropy; avoid in HFrEF"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "head": ["Drug", "Start dose", "Target / usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Amiodarone (oral)", "400 mg BID–TID load (~10 g total)", "100–200 mg daily maintenance", "Caution with known thyroid/pulmonary/hepatic disease if alternatives exist", "TFTs & LFTs q6mo, baseline PFTs/CXR, eye/skin; QT"], ["Sotalol", "80 mg BID", "120–160 mg BID", "CrCl <40, baseline QT >450 ms, decompensated HF", "Inpatient initiation with QT/telemetry; renal dosing"], ["Dofetilide", "125–500 mcg BID by CrCl/QT", "per nomogram", "CrCl <20, QT >440 ms, hypokalemia", "Mandatory 3-day inpatient telemetry load; strict K+/Mg2+/QT"], ["Flecainide", "50 mg BID", "100–150 mg BID", "Structural heart disease / CAD (CAST)", "Pair with AV-nodal agent to prevent 1:1 flutter; QRS width"], ["Dronedarone", "400 mg BID", "400 mg BID", "Permanent AF (PALLAS); NYHA III–IV or recent decompensated HF (ANDROMEDA)", "LFTs, HF status; less efficacy than amiodarone"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "Never give a Class IC agent (flecainide, propafenone) for AF without an AV-nodal blocker on board. IC drugs slow the atrial rate and can organize AF into a slower atrial flutter that then conducts 1:1 to the ventricle at 200+ bpm. And never use IC agents in structural heart disease — CAST showed excess mortality when they were used post-MI."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic</strong> — Vaughan Williams as <em>'Some Block Potassium Channels':</em> class <em>I</em> = <em>S</em>odium (Na), <em>II</em> = <em>B</em>eta-blockers, <em>III</em> = <em>P</em>otassium, <em>IV</em> = <em>C</em>alcium. For the IB subclass, 'IB is best for the brain and the heart-attack heart' — lidocaine works on ischemic ventricular tissue and causes CNS toxicity."}]}, {"id": "av-nodal-svt", "title": "Acute rate control, SVT, and the ablation endgame", "body": [{"type": "p", "text": "AV-nodal agents are the workhorses for acute rate control and for terminating AV-nodal-dependent SVT. The reflex to master is the narrow-complex regular tachycardia: vagal maneuvers first, then adenosine, which transiently blocks the AV node and either breaks a reentrant SVT or unmasks the underlying atrial rhythm (flutter waves, atrial tachycardia) when it does not."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "head": ["Drug", "Start / acute dose", "Use", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Adenosine", "6 mg rapid IV push, then 12 mg", "Terminate/unmask regular narrow SVT", "Avoid in bronchospasm; blunted by theophylline, potentiated by dipyridamole", "Continuous ECG (expect brief pause/flush); warn patient of chest sensation"], ["Diltiazem", "0.25 mg/kg IV, then infusion 5–15 mg/h", "Rate control AF/flutter, SVT", "HFrEF, hypotension, WPW with pre-excited AF", "BP, HR, telemetry"], ["Metoprolol", "2.5–5 mg IV q5min (up to 15 mg); 25 mg PO BID", "Rate control, ischemia", "Decompensated HF, severe brady, cocaine-related, pre-excited AF", "BP, HR, bronchospasm"], ["Digoxin", "0.25 mg IV q6h load (≤1.5 mg/24h)", "Rate control in HF/hypotension", "Renal failure, hypokalemia raises toxicity", "Level, K+, renal function; watch AV block"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "text": "In pre-excited atrial fibrillation (irregular, wide, very fast — AF conducting down an accessory pathway in WPW), AV-nodal blockers (adenosine, diltiazem, verapamil, beta-blockers, digoxin) are contraindicated. Blocking the node shunts conduction entirely down the accessory pathway and can accelerate to VF. Use procainamide or synchronized cardioversion."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "entries": [{"term": "AVNRT vs AVRT", "def": "AVNRT uses dual pathways within the AV node (commonest regular SVT). AVRT uses an accessory pathway (orthodromic = narrow, antidromic = wide). Both are AV-node dependent and usually break with adenosine, but AVRT with a manifest pathway (WPW) changes drug choice."}, {"term": "Catheter ablation", "def": "Definitive therapy for many SVTs, typical atrial flutter (cavotricuspid isthmus line), and AF (pulmonary vein isolation). For symptomatic AVNRT/AVRT and typical flutter, ablation cure rates are high and it is often preferred over lifelong drugs."}, {"term": "Pulmonary vein isolation", "def": "The cornerstone of AF ablation. Pulsed-field ablation (PFA) is a newer energy source that preferentially spares adjacent esophagus and phrenic nerve; CABANA and EAST-AFNET 4 support rhythm control, especially early and in HF (CASTLE-AF showed a mortality benefit of AF ablation in HFrEF)."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Typical atrial flutter is the SVT most worth recognizing cold: sawtooth flutter waves near 300 with 2:1 conduction give a suspiciously regular rate around 150. Adenosine will not fix it but will reveal it. Its anatomy — a macroreentrant circuit around the cavotricuspid isthmus — makes it one of the most curable arrhythmias in the lab, with high isthmus-line ablation success."}, {"type": "linkout", "text": "ECG library examples of AVNRT, WPW/pre-excitation, typical atrial flutter, and adenosine-unmasked rhythms.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL ECG Library — supraventricular tachycardias"}]}, {"id": "pitfalls", "title": "High-yield pitfalls and consult reflexes", "body": [{"type": "list", "depth": 1, "items": ["A shock coil on the RV lead means ICD or CRT-D — never call a device with a coil a 'pacemaker.'", "Magnet over a pacemaker → asynchronous pacing; magnet over an ICD → shocks off, pacing unchanged. Keep them separate.", "Do not implant a permanent device for a reversible bradycardia (drugs, Lyme, ischemia, electrolytes).", "Respect the 40-day-post-MI and 90-day-post-revascularization waiting periods before a primary-prevention ICD.", "Reassess EF after ~3 months of GDMT in new non-ischemic cardiomyopathy before committing to an ICD.", "CRT needs >98% biventricular pacing to work; a 'non-responder' with low BiV% has a fixable problem, not a failed therapy.", "Nonphysiologic high-rate noise on the ventricular electrogram with a rising lead impedance is lead fracture, not VT — a top cause of inappropriate shocks.", "Flecainide and propafenone are forbidden in structural heart disease and must be paired with an AV-nodal blocker in AF.", "AV-nodal blockers are dangerous in pre-excited AF; reach for procainamide or cardioversion."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "text": "When you get paged about any device patient, answer four questions before anything else: What is the device (from the film or interrogation)? Is the patient pacemaker-dependent? Is there a defibrillator to suspend? What does a magnet do to THIS device? Those four answers pre-empt almost every perioperative and code-blue device mistake."}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 72-year-old man is scheduled for an elective right hemicolectomy. His chest radiograph shows a left pre-pectoral generator with two leads: one ending in the right atrial appendage and one crossing to the right ventricular apex with a thick radiopaque segment along its distal course. He is not pacemaker-dependent on interrogation. The surgeon plans monopolar electrocautery. Which intraoperative strategy is most appropriate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Place a magnet over the device for the duration of the case"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Reprogram the device to VOO asynchronous pacing"}, {"key": "C", "text": "No device management is needed because he is not pacemaker-dependent"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Interrogate only after the case is finished"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Cancel surgery until the device is explanted"}], "correct": "A", "explanation": "The thick radiopaque segment on the RV lead is a shock coil, so this is a dual-chamber ICD. Monopolar cautery can be oversensed as VF and trigger an inappropriate shock, so tachytherapy must be suspended. Because he is NOT pacemaker-dependent, a magnet — which suspends ICD shocks while leaving pacing untouched — is sufficient and reversible. Reprogramming to VOO (B) addresses pacing inhibition, which is not the threat here since he is not dependent. Doing nothing (C) leaves him exposed to an inappropriate shock. Post-op-only interrogation (D) ignores the intraoperative risk."}, {"stem": "A 66-year-old woman with non-ischemic cardiomyopathy has an LVEF of 30% and NYHA class III symptoms despite three months of optimized guideline-directed therapy. Her ECG shows sinus rhythm with a left bundle branch block and a QRS of 164 ms. Which device offers the greatest expected benefit?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Single-chamber VVI pacemaker"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Subcutaneous ICD"}, {"key": "C", "text": "CRT-D (biventricular ICD)"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Dual-chamber DDD pacemaker"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Leadless pacemaker"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "She is the archetypal CRT responder: LVEF ≤35%, LBBB morphology, QRS ≥150 ms, sinus rhythm, ambulatory NYHA III on GDMT — and female sex further favors response. She also meets primary-prevention ICD criteria (EF ≤35%, non-ischemic, on GDMT), so a combined CRT-D captures both resynchronization and defibrillation benefit. A plain S-ICD (B) defibrillates but cannot resynchronize. Pacemakers (A, D, E) neither resynchronize the wide-QRS ventricle nor protect against sudden death."}, {"stem": "A 24-year-old man presents with a wide-complex, irregular tachycardia at rates up to 240 bpm. His baseline ECG on a prior visit showed a short PR interval and a delta wave. He is alert with a blood pressure of 110/70. Which is the most appropriate acute therapy?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Intravenous diltiazem"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Intravenous adenosine"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Intravenous metoprolol"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Intravenous procainamide"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Intravenous digoxin"}], "correct": "D", "explanation": "The delta wave and short PR indicate WPW, and an irregular wide fast tachycardia is pre-excited atrial fibrillation conducting down the accessory pathway. AV-nodal blockers — diltiazem, adenosine, metoprolol, digoxin — are contraindicated because blocking the node forces all conduction down the accessory pathway and can precipitate VF. Procainamide slows accessory-pathway conduction and is the correct pharmacologic choice; synchronized cardioversion is appropriate if unstable."}, {"stem": "During routine interrogation of a CRT-D implanted 10 months ago, a patient whose heart failure symptoms have not improved is found to have a biventricular pacing percentage of 84%. Atrial fibrillation with a moderately controlled ventricular response is noted in the arrhythmia log. Which intervention is most likely to restore CRT benefit?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Increase the programmed lower rate limit only"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Conclude the patient is a CRT non-responder and stop pursuing resynchronization"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Improve rate control and consider AV-junction ablation to achieve near-100% biventricular pacing"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Turn off the left ventricular lead"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Reduce guideline-directed heart failure medications"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "CRT works only when both ventricles are captured nearly all the time; a BiV pacing percentage of 84% means intrinsically conducted AF beats are stealing resynchronization. The fix is to maximize BiV pacing — aggressive rate control and, when native conduction still competes, AV-junction ablation to force ~100% capture. Labeling this a non-responder (B) is premature when the pacing percentage is the correctable problem. Turning off the LV lead (D) or cutting HF therapy (E) would worsen outcomes."}, {"stem": "A pacemaker interrogation on a 78-year-old with a dual-chamber device reports a stable, low ventricular capture threshold, normal R-wave sensing, a ventricular lead impedance of 520 ohms, and a battery status of 'RRT/ERI' with an estimated 6 weeks of longevity. The patient is asymptomatic. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Immediate lead revision"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Schedule elective generator replacement within the coming weeks"}, {"key": "C", "text": "No action; RRT is a normal finding at every visit"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Emergent generator change tonight"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Increase the pacing output to preserve battery"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "RRT/ERI (recommended replacement time / elective replacement indicator) signals the battery is nearing end of service and the generator should be changed electively, typically within weeks, before it reaches EOL where the device may drop to a limited backup mode. The leads are healthy (normal impedance, stable threshold, good sensing), so no lead revision (A) is needed. RRT is not a routine baseline finding (C), it is not an emergency in an asymptomatic, well-paced patient (D), and increasing output (E) would drain the battery faster."}], "references": ["2018 ACC/AHA/HRS Guideline on the Evaluation and Management of Patients With Bradycardia and Cardiac Conduction Delay", "2017 AHA/ACC/HRS Guideline for Management of Patients With Ventricular Arrhythmias and the Prevention of Sudden Cardiac Death", "2012/2013 ACCF/AHA/HRS Focused Update on Device-Based Therapy of Cardiac Rhythm Abnormalities (CRT and ICD indications)", "2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure (GDMT, ICD and CRT recommendations)", "2023 ACC/AHA/ACCP/HRS Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Atrial Fibrillation", "Heart Rhythm Society / ASA Expert Consensus Statement on the Perioperative Management of Patients With Cardiac Implantable Electronic Devices", "HRS Expert Consensus Statement on MRI and Radiation Exposure in Patients With Cardiovascular Implantable Electronic Devices", "Landmark trials: MADIT-II, SCD-HeFT, DINAMIT, IRIS, DANISH, MADIT-RIT, CARE-HF, MADIT-CRT, RAFT, CAST, ANDROMEDA, PALLAS, CASTLE-AF, EAST-AFNET 4, ARTESIA, NOAH-AFNET 6"]};
